equently habituated the discourses of U.S. foreign policy.  This collection of essays focuses on counter-identities in American consciousness to explain how foreign policies and the discourse surrounding them develop.  Whether it is the seemingly ubiquitous evil of Hitler during World War II or the more complicated perceptions of communism throughout the Cold War, these essays illuminate the cultural contexts that constructed rival identities.  The authors challenge our understanding of “others,” looking at early applications of the concept in the eighteenth century to recent twenty-first century conflicts, establishing how this phenomenon is central to decision making through centuries of conflict.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aOther (Philosophy) 0aOther (Philosophy). 0aOther minds (Theory of knowledge). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAdib-Moghaddam, Arshin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmbrosius, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullinane, Michael Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullinane, Michael Patrick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreene, Jack P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHixson, Walter L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoganson, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Liam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKidd, Geraldine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMariano, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Michaela Hoenicke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela